  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Assessing customer risk profiles\n- Conducting background checks\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Monitoring and documenting unusual financial activities\n\n3. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Documenting customer identification information\n- Retaining records for specified periods\n\n4. Compliance Programs\n- Implementing internal AML policies\n- Training employees on AML regulations\n- Establishing monitoring systems\n\n5. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying potential money laundering risks\n- Developing strategies to mitigate those risks\n- Conducting periodic risk assessments\n\n6. Regulatory Compliance\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Adhering to Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Complying with local and international AML regulations\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, fines, and potential criminal charges.\n\nThese requirements aim to prevent financial crimes and help track potentially illegal financial activities.",
